'''Robert Herron''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|h|ɛr|ɒ|n}} {{respell|HERR|on}}; born June 2, 1992) is a former [[American football]] [[wide receiver]]. He was drafted by the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in the sixth round of the [[2014 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Wyoming Cowboys football|Wyoming]].

==Early years==
Herron was born in [[Los Angeles, California]]. He was raised by his fathers cousin because his father was in prison and his mother was not a "consistent presence".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/former-wyoming-wr-robert-herron-s-past-drives-him-to-succeed-031214|title=Former Wyoming WR Robert Herron's past drives him to succeed|last=Jones|first=Ross|website=FOX Sports|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> He attended [[Susan Miller Dorsey High School]] in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/16/sports/la-sp-sondheimer-20140317|title=Robert Herron hopes to be among NFL draftees from Southern California|last=Sondheimer|first=Eric|date=2014-03-16|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> As a senior, he caught 24 passes for 600 yards and six touchdowns, while adding 15 carries for 171 yards and three touchdowns. He earned him first team all-city and all-league honors, and helped guide his team to an appearance in the semifinals of the state playoffs.

Along with playing football, Herron also ran [[track and field]]. He lettered as a sprinter in his final two years. He posted a career-best time  of 10.5 seconds in the [[100 meters]], while also running the [[200 meters]] in 20.99 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ca.milesplit.com/athletes/778894-robert-herron/feed#.VAVmhvmSwrk|title=Robert Herron - Stats|website=California MileSplit|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref>

==College career==
Herron attended the [[University of Wyoming]] from 2010 to 2013. Upon arriving at Wyoming, he signed so late in the process that he missed all of the summer camps and workouts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1936140-wyoming-wide-receiver-robert-herron-never-had-it-easy|title=WR Herron: From Hard Beginnings to Draft Riser|last=Kissel|first=BJ|website=Bleacher Report|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> Despite this, he split time at [[wide receiver]] and [[running back]], as he appeared in 10 of 12 games as a freshman in 2010. He carried the ball 40 times for 235 yards (5.9 avg), and caught 6 passes for 57 yards.

In 2011, predominantly playing wide receiver, he started the season catching seven passes for 104 yards and two touchdowns, including the game-winning touchdown with 22 seconds left in the fourth quarter vs. [[Weber State Wildcats football|Weber State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trib.com/college/wyoming/wyoming-football-notes-alexander-herron-set-marks-in-season-opener/article_c855a09b-b44b-5323-8e42-41a32f9b3f7c.html|title=Wyoming football notes: Alexander, Herron set marks in season opener|last=writer|first=ERIC SCHMOLDT Star-Tribune staff|website=Casper Star-Tribune Online|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> Herron finished his season second on the team with 43 receptions for 379 yards and three touchdowns.

In 2012, Herron established himself as a deep threat receiver, averaging 21.2 yds per reception. Opening the season vs #15 [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]], he had a breakout performance, totaling five catches for 173 yards and two touchdowns, becoming the National Receiver of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gowyo.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090312aac.html|title=Robert Herron Earns National Wide Receiver of the Week Honors|website=www.gowyo.com|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> He went on to catch 31 passes for 657 yards and eight touchdowns as a junior.

In 2013, as a senior, Herron set career highs in receptions (72), receiving yards (937), and touchdowns (9). In Wyoming's final home game, Herron recorded 11 catches, 141 receiving yards and four touchdowns in a 59–56 overtime win over [[Hawaii Warriors football|Hawaii]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trib.com/sports/college/wyoming/herron-scores-four-tds-in-final-cowboys-home-game/article_27152c36-1a33-59d6-b480-1f4d9fb94ae3.html|title=Herron scores four TDs in final Cowboys home game|last=writer|first=MIKE VOREL Star-Tribune staff|website=Casper Star-Tribune Online|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref> His four TD receptions in the game tied the school record set by [[Marcus Harris (American football, born 1974)|Marcus Davis]] in 1995. He earned honorable mention All-[[Mountain West Conference|MWC]] honors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gowyo.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121013aaa.html|title=Five Wyoming Cowboys Earn All-Mountain West Conference Honors|website=www.gowyo.com|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref>

During his career he played in 42 games, finishing with 152 receptions for 2,030 yards and 20 [[touchdowns]]. After his senior season he was invited to the [[2014 Senior Bowl|Senior Bowl]] and [[NFL Combine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trib.com/news/opinion/blogs/cowboys/wyoming-wr-robert-herron-impresses-in-first-senior-bowl-practice/article_89bab3aa-09ee-5287-866d-8b54824e9609.html|title=Wyoming WR Robert Herron impresses in first Senior Bowl practice|last=writer|first=MIKE VOREL Star-Tribune staff|website=Casper Star-Tribune Online|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trib.com/news/opinion/blogs/cowboys/former-wyoming-wr-herron-completes-nfl-combine-workout/article_677555e7-6811-5d60-9088-82b6f87e8741.html|title=Former Wyoming WR Herron completes NFL Combine workout|last=writer|first=MIKE VOREL Star-Tribune staff|website=Casper Star-Tribune Online|access-date=2016-05-14}}</ref>

